  "summary": "Detective Inspector Dick Hakast arrives at 19 Wilbraham Crescent to investigate a murder. A man has been found dead on the floor, likely stabbed approximately thirty minutes prior. The house is owned by Miss Mirella Pembleton (also referred to as Miss Pema, Miss Pemah, or Miss Permshaw), a teacher at the Allenburg Institute who teaches blind script to disabled children.\n\nHakast interviews Hilary Webber, a stenographer from Cavendish Document Printing Agency, in the kitchen. Webber explains that she was sent to the house at 3:00 p.m. by her employer, Miss Martin, specifically at the request of Miss Pembleton. Webber discovered the body after turning a sofa and admitted to touching the corpse, which left her hands covered in blood. She noted a strange discrepancy with the house's clocks: while the cuckoo clock struck three, other clocks were nearly an hour ahead. Webber claims she entered the house because Miss Pembleton told her to come in, despite the two not having spoken previously. Webber, who lives with her aunt Mrs. Lott, appeared visibly shaken and fearful during the questioning.\n\nAfter dismissing Webber to the dining room, Hakast prepares to interview Miss Pembleton. As he approaches her, she demonstrates her blindness by feeling her way to a chair. Before the interview begins, Miss Pembleton questions Hakast about the identity and presence of Colin Lum, a man who had been present at the scene.",
